window.docContents[99].resolve({"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project--The-valence-formula":{"contents":"The valence (weight) formula for .\nLet  and let  be a nonzero modular form on\nthe full modular group. Then the orders of vanishing of  over the -orbits\nin  satisfy\n\nwhere the final sum runs over the -orbits other than those of  and\n, and  is the order of vanishing at any representative\nof the orbit (well-defined by ).\nFormalised in LeanModularForms: valence_formula_textbook — sorry-free.Depends on:  \n\nThe proof is the textbook contour-integral argument (Diamond–Shurman 3.1.1) made rigorous through a\ngeneralised residue theorem. One integrates the logarithmic derivative  around the boundary\n of the standard fundamental domain truncated at height , using the\nHungerbühler–Wasem generalised winding-number machinery to handle the corners and the elliptic\nfixed points. The simple poles of  inside  are exactly the zeros of , each\ncontributing its order of vanishing as residue. The boundary contributions evaluate term by term:\nthe top horizontal segment yields  via the -expansion\n(); the two vertical edges cancel under -invariance and the two arcs\ncombine under -invariance (); and the explicit winding numbers\n at  and  at  (and ) produce the fractional\ncoefficients  and  together with the global . Equating the residue sum\nto the boundary integral and rearranging gives the stated identity.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Modular and Automorphic Forms\u0009Results from the LeanModularForms project","header":"6.8.6. The valence formula","id":"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project--The-valence-formula"}});